ce:section.ce:para:
The specificity of the sensor with cTnI and other non-specific possible antigens such as Hepatitis C antigen (HsC), Cyclic citrullinated peptide antigen (CCP), Interleukin 1-Beta (IL-1β) and Gliadin that are released into the human blood in case of hepatitis, rheumatic arthritis (RA) in various infections and wheat allergy, respectively were carried out as described in DPV measurement. The DPV peak current (Ip) of the sensor after 10min incubation (as described for cTnI) with 1pg per 6μL of non-specific antigens were found to be almost same or slightly reduced from the immobilized anti-cTnI probe whereas with cTnI shows comparatively reduced Ip due to interaction (binding) with anti-cTnI (Fig. 5
                        ). The significant decrease in Ip value was obtained only in the case of cTnI, which confirms the specificity of the sensor only to cTnI. The inset shows bar graph for relative peak current (Fig. 5a) and% relative peak current (Fig. 5b) with target and mismatched antigens. The stability of the immobilized probe electrode was studied by measuring change in the DPV peak current every 30days of storage at 4°C. The sensor electrode was found to be stable for 6 months at 4°C only with 10% loss in the initial Ip of the immobilized probe. The comparison of our method (GQD-PAMAM nanohybrid based sensor) with earlier reported methods for the detection of cTnI causing human heart attack is summarized in Table 1
                        .
